Avoid propranolol and other non selective beta blocker -> can increase uterine irritability. Atenolol has been associated with lower foetal weight. Avoid.
Avoid nitroprusside -> risk of foetal cyanide poisoning.

3-methoxy-4-hydroxy-mandelic acid = vanillylmandelic acid

Significance of the meningococcal rash

  • Pathogenesis: probably because of dermal microvessel injury and thrombosis leading to haemorrhagic skin necrosis and thrombocytopenia.
  • Rash is very common: Over 50% of patients have the rash on presentation. More on the trunk and lower body.
  • Severity of rash correlates with
    • Degree of thrombocytopenia
    • Risk of developing DIC!

Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction

Jarisch Herxheimer reaction (JHR) is

  • a transient clinical phenomenon that occurs in patients infected by spirochetes who undergo antibiotic treatment.
  • The reaction occurs within 24 hours of antibiotic treatment of spirochete infections, including syphilis, leptospirosis, Lyme disease, and relapsing feve
  • Symptoms: fever, chills, rigors, tachycardia, hypotension.
  • Usually quickly resolves on cessation of antibiotics.
  • Antibiotics can then be reinstated.
  • Hypotension can become life threatening.
  • Pathogenesis unknonw -> possibly immune reaction to lysed spirochetal cells.

Non selective beta blockers
Mnemonic: Non-CLAPS

  • Carvedilol

  • labetalol

  • Propranolol

  • Sotalol

  • Starting beta blockers prior to high risk surgery is controversial.

  • Beta blockers can increase weight by as much as 1.2 Kg

  • Beta blockers must be avoided in acute heart failure.

  • Beta blockers can cause hyperkalemia.

  • Lipophillic beta blockers cross the BBB and cause CNS side effects.

  • Cardioselective beta blockers CAN be used in COPD patients.

  • HMG-CoA reductase: Rate limiting enzyme in cholesterol sythesis : found in the liver and ? other tissues
  • LCAT : the enzyme synthesized by the liver and attached to HDL which exterifies cholesterol so that it becomes trapped inside HDL (once the HDL has taken up cholesterol from tissues using the ABC-A1 protein) Required for reverse transport of cholesterol.
  • LPL: lipoprotein lipase: the enzyme found on tissues which removes lipids from VLDL and it's derivatives, increasing their density.

Hepatic disease

  • Reduce TGL by 20-70%

  • Incrase HDL

  • SE: myositis, nausea, reversible increase in creatinine.

  • DO NOT combine gemfibrozil with statins

  • Inhibits rate limiting step (HMG-CoA reductase) in cholesterol synthesis.

  • Most potent are atorvastatin and rosuvastatin.

  • Reduce LDL by 30-60%.

  • Modest effect on TGL

  • Little effect on HDL

  • SE: muscle aches, rhabdomyolysis

  • Should not be used in pregnancy
    Reduce alcohol consumption, increase cholesterol binding foods like bran and soy protein.

Acute screening of HIV infection

[!TIP] Summary
Combined antigen + antibody tests are preferred as they have a shorter window period of about 4 weeks.

  • eg: patient presents with inguinal lymphadenopathy 1 month after unprotected sexual intercourse.
  • Screening is now done with combined p24 antigen + Antibody test. (i.e "fourth generation" tests)
  • Antibody test alone may not the sensitive enough within 6 weeks after exposure.
  • Antigen tests become positive 2 - 3 weeks after exposure.
  • However, most rapid tests are antibody tests. They can begin detecting HIV from 18-90 days after exposure.

[!INFO] What is a window period?
Source
The time taken from exposure to the test becoming positive for a given percentage of positive patients.

  • By 6 weeks, 99% of combined antigen/antibody tests for HIV will be +ve. If negative at this stage, there's no need to for repeat testing. (and at 4 weeks, 95%)
  • In contrast, the antigen test alone is positive in 99% at only 60 days. (roughly 2 months)
  • Negative test results done within the window period must be repeated after the window period elapses.

Chronic phase

- Acute or subacute onset of **proximal muscle weakness** associated with constitutional symptoms. *Laryngeal and respiratory muscles are affected* without treatment.
  • Examples of GPCR based signalling pathways: catecholamines, histamine, serotonin, opioids, cannabinoid, amines, peptides, prostanoids.
  • The third transmembrane domain can bind to 'G proteins' on the intracellular side.
    1. Adenylyl cyclase - an enzyme which synthesizes cAMP from ATP, when activated.
    2. Phospholipase C and inositol:
    3. Rho A / Rho kinase - involved in cell growth pathways and smooth muscle contraction
    4. MAP kinase - mitogen-activated protein kinase - . (controls things like cell division)
  • Note that stimulation of Galpha-s associated receptors activates adenylyl cyclase but stimulation of G-alpha-i associated receptors inactivates adenylyl cyclase.
  • cAMP - generated by activation of adenylyl cyclase (the green AC in the diagram)- activates protein kinases.

[!INFO] An illustration of receptor actions

Actions of adrenaline:

  • on Alpha receptors -> vasoconstriction
  • on Beta receptors -> vasolidation

  • ![Hormone Physiology#Adrenaline synthesis](Hormone Physiology#Adrenaline synthesis)
  • Presentation: Continous OR intermittent symptoms.
    • Can cause sudden death! -> patients with phaeochromocytoma must be investigated.
    • Mnemonic: Phaeochromocytoma is associated with 1,2,3 :
      NF-1, MEN 2, VHL (chromosome 3)
    • Three Negative 24 hour urinary metanephrine levels excludes the diagnosis. -> so used as a screening test.

    • Urinary VMA and catecholamines are less sensitive and specific.

    • Alpha blockade (phenoxybenzamine) must precede beta blockade (propranolol)

The intercalated cells are responsible for H+ secretion and chloride secretion.
